{{ja-kanjitab|あお|yomi=k}}
{{IPAchar|/sawo/}} {{q|uncertain, may be compound as opposed to root}} → {{IPAchar|/awo/}} → {{IPAchar|/ao/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=あお|-}}, ultimately from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*awo}}.<ref>Thomas Pellard.  [https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01289288/document Ryukyuan perspectives on the proto-Japonic vowel system].  Frellesvig, Bjarke; Sells, Peter. Japanese/Korean Linguistics 20, CSLI Publications, pp.81–96, 2013.</ref>

Appears as the latter part in older compounds with an ''-s-'' infix or prefix. It is unclear if this leading {{IPAchar|/s/}} is indicative of an earlier form (''sawo''), or if this was an addition for [[euphony]] to avoid vowel clusters, or for other reasons. This {{IPAchar|/s/}} is also seen in {{m|ja|雨|tr=ame||[[rain]]|pos=becoming ''same'' in old compounds}} and {{m|ja|稲|tr=ine||[[rice]]|pos=becoming ''shine'' in old compounds}}.

Given that this {{IPAchar|/s/}} only ever appears interstitially, and given the semantics, this {{IPAchar|/s/}} may be cognate with {{cog|ko|-}} interfix {{m|ko|ᄉ|-ᄉ-|tr=-s-}} used to mark possession; compare {{nc|de|-s-}}.

